font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">f </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">iQuanta</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> D</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ata.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The guidance for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">iQuanta</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> states that forces should use the data to compare themselves against the average of most similar forces (MSF). </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Senior managers up to Chief Officer level </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">blatantly ignored this guidance despite representations from within the performance team.  They </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">demand</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ed to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> be told ‘what number they were in their family of forces’.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  If they were</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> second they wanted to be first.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Through adopting this approach managers would again bring pressure to bear on improving the numbers rather than improving the level of performance.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A lack of understanding of twelve month</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">/three month</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> rolling data also lead to insufficient time being giv</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">en to initiatives to reduce crime to achieve results.  Instant results were expected/demanded from operational colleagues.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">HMIC Inspection</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> – The Crime Scene</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">During the visit to Wiltshire Police by HMIC in 2011 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in support of their thematic inspection ‘Cr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ime Scene’ </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">around 120 incidents</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> were assessed to see if they had been correctly recorded as a crime.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It was clear that the only issues raised were where an incident that they felt should have been recording as a crime hadn’t been.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I raised directly with</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the inspectors why they had not identified incidents that had been recorded crime where there was credible evidence to the contrary.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The view from the lead Inspector (Superintendent Steve Wallace – Hants Police) was that if a victim thought it was a crim</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e then it should be recorded as such.  Proportionality would come in the investigative stage following an incident being recorded as a crime.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Superintendent Wallace cited his previous experience as a crime registrar in Hampshire Police.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The ACPO report</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> – Understanding Crime Recording also raises the issue that HMIC and crime registrars interpret the question of ‘when to record’ in this way.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> view was also shar</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ed by our force crime registrar.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Over recording of crimes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">On becoming Chief Constable </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of Wiltshire Brian Moore set out to make Wiltshire the “Safest in the Country”.  This became interpreted internally to a more measurable ‘lowest rates of violent crime in the country’.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">6.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">During the summer of 2010, in my role as Performance Manager, I identi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">fied that Wiltshire Police had significantly higher rates of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">no crime</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> for less serious assaults than the other ‘top ten forces’ with the lowest violent crime rates.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">6.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Analysis showed that in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">excess</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of 2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">0</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">% of these had been recorded as ‘no crimes’ within f</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ive days of the initial report.  At the time force procedures were such that the additional verifiable information (AVI) required to achieve a ‘no crime’ decision often needed to be in documentary form e.g. statement. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">6.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It became clear to me that for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">these</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> crimes the AVI would have been available following basic and straightforward enquiries.  I further hypothesised there was a high level of probability that AVI </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">either had been or </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">could have been established within the 3x24 hour period allowed by NCRS to ma</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ke a decision as to whether to record as a crime.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">6.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I further hypothesised there was a high probability that there were other crimes </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with information </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">which, whilst </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">it</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> would not satisfy the requirement of AVI, would have ‘credible evidence to the contrary’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">6.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">One of the key differences with reported common assaults</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, as compared to other crime types, is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">overwhelming</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> majority of cases the ‘offender’ is known</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, and named,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> by the victim.  This provides an opportunity to quickly identify an alternati</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ve version of events (as there invariably is) and ethically apply the NCRS threshold test</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> e.g.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> do the circumstances amount to a crime in law AND that there </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">no</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> credible evidence to the contrary.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">6.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Analysis of a significant sample of common assaults was c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">arried out by myself and a temporary Inspector on our team who had extensive experience as a detective</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">6.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We took a deliberately literal inte</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rpretation of the words of NCRS specifically around the balance of probabilities that it was more likely than not th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">at the incident was as the result of a criminal act and whether there was any other credible evidence.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">6.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There does however seem to be a contradiction with NCRS which states it is for the police to determine whether a crime has been committed but states t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hat in most cases the belief by the victim that a crime has occurred is sufficient to justify its recording.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">6.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Our analysis showed that in around 40% of the cases we examined there was other evidence that gave an alternative version of events that could be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">deemed credible.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">6.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This is not to suggest that 40% had been incorrectly recorded.  What we concluded however was that there was a significant risk that crimes were being re</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">corded that shouldn’t have been due to a lack of recognition of credible evidence </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to the contrary.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">6.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In many cases the incidents occur when only the victim and offender are present and there is an absence of forensic evidence.  This presents the police with a significant dilemma. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">6.13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">To verify our findings we sought an independent operat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ional Detective Sergeant to also make an independent assessment of the same incidents.  The findings of t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">his DS supported our findings.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">6.14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Similar issues are also raised in the NPIA – Understanding Crime Recording</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">which is available on the College of Policin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">g Website.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">6.15</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Understanding Crime Recording report encourages ‘greater use of professional judgement in relation to all aspects of the crime recording process and in particular around what constitutes ‘credible evidence to the contrary’ and ‘additional v</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">erifiable information’.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Impacts of the over recording of crime.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">over </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">recording of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">crime </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">can have significant impacts on individuals </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and police resources.  It can risk public confidence in the police.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Quite rightly there is an expectation that police will deal with identified suspects expeditiously.  Often the method of ‘dealing with’ suspects of violent crime is to invoke the power of arrest.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Within Wiltshire Police once a violent crime ha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> been rec</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">orded as such and a suspect named and linked to that crime there </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">was</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a performance culture linked to ‘customer satisfaction’ and  ‘detection rates’ which place</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> insurmountable pressure on officers to make arrests.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As a local Joint Branch Board we are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">currently supporting an ex-officer who has suffered significant psychological damage as a result of an unnecessary arrest related to a dubious decision making process in relation to an allegation of fraud.  This has had a significant on her life.  Often as</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> police officers we forget the impact that an arrest can have</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> on individuals</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">When incidents are not recorded as crimes there is less pressure</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to make arrests</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  As a result investigating officers have more scope to use professional judgement</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in the inve</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">stigation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Conversely with increased opportunities for use of professional judgement comes an increased risk that crimes that should have been recorded as crimes haven’t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> been</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  Clear strategies need to be in place to mitigate these risks.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The culture of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Wiltshire police </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">had a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tend</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ency</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for strategic </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">focus </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">on the outcomes of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">investigations </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">into recorded crime </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rather than the quality and integrity of investigations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> into reported incidents</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In respect of recorded crime this</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">improved in late 2011 w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ith an understanding that victim satisfaction survey results had identified low levels of satisfaction with the quality of the investigations.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A plan to improve quality of investigations was implemented and showed positive results.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The same focus was n</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ot given to the investigation of incidents</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> constant pressure at all levels of management to improve detection rates</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As Wiltshire’s single point of contact for the National Crime mapping system when it went live I received numerous ‘complaints’ from people about the level of crime in their neighbourhoods.  It became evident that people had concerns that high crime levels</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> may affect property prices.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">One of the other concerns that I have is around enhanced vetting.  Where people are named as suspects against recorded crimes there can be a requirement to disclose.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In one example I was made aware of related to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a decision </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for disclosure that had been referred to the Assistant Chief Constable for a determination.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">During an enhanced CRB check on an individual it became apparent that he was the ‘suspect’ in an allegation of child abuse (physical).  The circumstances were that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the allegation had been made by his ex-wife some time after they had separated.  The reporting person wished no further action.  The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">report however </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">was recorded as a crime and the ‘suspect’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> was never approached or advised of the allegation. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.15</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The absence of an investigation and the failure to identify any potential evidence to the contrary could have had a significant impact on the job prospects of the accused.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.16</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In my view this risks undermining one of the foundations of our criminal justice </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">system of being ‘innocent until proven guilty.’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span>